mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Aileen, Brendan, Cathal, Conor, Eamon, Keelin, Liam, Michael Sean, Niall, Ronan, Sean Patrick.","Irish: from <b>Caomhánach</b>, an adjectival epithet meaning ‘belonging to (Saint) <i>Caomhán</i>’, whose personal name means ‘little beautiful one’. Etymologically, the first part of the name is the same as that in   Kevin  .","History: The first known bearer of the epithet was Domhnall Caomhánach (Donal Kavanagh, died in 1175), the son of Diarmait Mac Murchadha (Dermot McMurrough), king of Leinster in the 12th century. Despite being killed at an early age, Domhnall Caomhánach gave his name to a large and important family in Irish history."],"variants":[{"name":"Kinsella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Donal, Finbar, Fintan.","Irish (Wexford and Carlow): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Cinnsealach</b>, or occasionally <b>Ó Cinnsealaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cinnsealach</i>’, an adjectival personal name meaning ‘proud, masterful’ or ‘chief warrior’. <i>Cinnsealach</i> can also indicate a member of the older population grouping called <i>Uí Chinnsealaigh</i>; compare the origin of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kevin","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Caoimhín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Caoimhín</i>’ (the personal name <i>Kevin</i>), a name derived from <i>Caémgein</i> ‘comely birth’ although now regarded as a diminutive of Gaelic <i>caomh</i> ‘comely, beloved’. Compare   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Aileen, Dermod, Donal, Patrick Sean.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanah","meanings":["with stress on the first syllable, this is a shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Caomhánach</b>, see   Kavanagh  .","alternatively, with stress on <i>-van-</i>, this is a shortened form of <b>McCavana</b>, from <b>Mac an Mhanaigh</b>, ‘son of the monk’ (from <i>manach</i> ‘monk’). This was a Mayo surname, also Anglicized by translation as   Monk   and   Monks  .","Irish:"]},{"name":"Cavender","meanings":["English: most probably a nickname from an Anglo-Norman French equivalent of French <i>chavender</i> ‘chub’ (the fish).","English (of Irish origin): Anglicized form of   Kavanagh   (and its variants, including <b>Cavenagh</b>) or   Cavanna  . Compare   Cavinder  .","History: Hugh Cavenagh (died <i>c.</i> 1709) came from Bristol in England to Westmoreland County, VA, in 1658 as an indentured servant for a five-year period to a Mr. Wills. His descendants spell their name mainly <i>Cavender</i> and <i>Cavinder</i>."]},{"name":"Kaveney","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Géibheannaigh</b> or <b>Mac Géibheannaigh</b>, ‘descendant or son of <i>Géibheannach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>géibheannach</i> meaning ‘bound, or captive one’. There may have been some confusion between this name and   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanagh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Fergus.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Oonagh.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary MacMorough Kavanagh was born in 1223, in Leinster, Ireland as the daughter of Mac Morough Donell Oge Kavanagh. She married William Le Gras in 1244, in County Kilkenny, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1223–":"1223–Surnud","1223–Female":"1223–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1245–1302":"1245–1302","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1302":"1302","1223":"1223","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","       1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1197":"1197",", Leinster, Ireland, Ireland":"Leinster, Iirimaa","Courtstown Castle,Kilkenny,Ireland":"Courtstown Castle, County Kilkenny, Iirimaa",", Kilkenny, Ireland, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1223–":"1223–Kuollut","1223–Female":"1223–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1245–1302":"1245–1302","1197–Male":"1197–Kuollut","1302":"1302","1223":"1223","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","       1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1197":"1197",", Leinster, Ireland, Ireland":"Leinster, Irlanti","Courtstown Castle,Kilkenny,Ireland":"Courtstown Castle, County Kilkenny, Irlanti",", Kilkenny, Ireland, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1223–":"1223–Décédée","1223–Female":"1223–Décédée","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1245–1302":"1245–1302","1197–Male":"1197–Décédé","1302":"1302","1223":"1223","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","       1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1197":"1197",", Leinster, Ireland, Ireland":"Leinster, Irlande","Courtstown Castle,Kilkenny,Ireland":"Courtstown Castle, County Kilkenny, Irlande",", Kilkenny, Ireland, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Mary MacMorough Kavanagh est née en 1223, à Leinster, Irlande, fille de Mac Morough Donell Oge Kavanagh. Elle a épousé William Le Gras en 1244, à County Kilkenny, Irlande. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1223–":"1223